@article{Elmegreen1999,
abstract = {Observed variations in the slope of the stellar initial mass function$\backslash$n(IMF) are shown to be consistent with a previously introduced model in$\backslash$nwhich the protostellar gas is randomly sampled from clouds with a$\backslash$nself-similar hierarchical structure. Root mean square variations in the$\backslash$nIMF slope around the Salpeter value are +/-0.4 when only 100 stars are$\backslash$nobserved, and +/-0.1 when 1000 stars are observed. Similar variations$\backslash$nshould be present in other stochastic models as well. The hierarchical$\backslash$nsampling model reproduces the tendency for massive stars to form closer$\backslash$nto the center of a cloud at a time somewhat later than the formation$\backslash$ntime of the lower mass stars. The systematic variation in birth position$\backslash$nresults from the tendency for the trunk and larger branches of the$\backslash$nhierarchical tree of cloud structure to lie closer to the cloud center,$\backslash$nwhile the variations in birth order result from the relative infrequency$\backslash$nof stars with larger masses. The hierarchical cloud sampling model has$\backslash$nnow reproduced most of the reliably observed features of the cluster$\backslash$nIMF. The power-law part of the IMF comes from cloud hierarchical$\backslash$nstructure that is sampled during various star formation processes with a$\backslash$nrelative rate proportional to the square root of the local density.$\backslash$nThese processes include turbulence compression, magnetic diffusion,$\backslash$ngravitational collapse, and clump or wavepacket coalescence, all of$\backslash$nwhich have about this rate dependence. The low-mass flattening comes$\backslash$nfrom the inability of gas to form stars below the thermal Jeans mass at$\backslash$ntypical temperatures and pressures. The thermal Jeans mass is the only$\backslash$nrelevant scale in the problem. Considerations of heating and cooling$\backslash$nprocesses indicate why the thermal Jeans mass should be nearly constant$\backslash$nin normal environments and why this mass might increase in starburst$\backslash$nregions. In particular, the relative abundance of high-mass stars should$\backslash$nincrease where the average density of the interstellar medium is very$\backslash$nlarge; accompanying this increase should be an increase in the average$\backslash$ntotal efficiency of star formation. Alternative models in which the rate$\backslash$nof star formation is independent of density and the local efficiency$\backslash$ndecreases systematically with increasing stellar mass can also reproduce$\backslash$nthe IMF, but this is an adjustable result and not a fundamental property$\backslash$nof hierarchical cloud structure, as is the preferred model. The steep$\backslash$nIMF in the extreme field is not explained by the model, but other$\backslash$norigins are suggested, including one in which massive stars in$\backslash$nlow-pressure environments halt star formation in their clouds. In this$\backslash$ncase, the slope of the extreme field IMF is independent of the slope of$\backslash$neach component cluster IMF and is given by (gamma-1)/alpha for a cloud$\backslash$nmass function slope, -gamma{\~{}}-2, and a power-law relation, M{\_}L{\~{}}M{\^{}}alpha{\_}c,$\backslash$nbetween the largest star in a low-pressure cloud, M{\_}L, and the cloud$\backslash$nmass, M{\_}c. A value of alpha{\~{}}1/4 is required to explain the extreme field$\backslash$nIMF as a superposition of individual cluster IMFs; cloud destruction by$\backslash$nionizing has this property. We note that the similarity between cluster$\backslash$nIMFs and the average IMF from global studies of galaxies implies that$\backslash$nmost stars form in clusters and that massive stars do not generally halt$\backslash$nstar formation in the same cloud.$\backslash$n},
